reviews.review_text: Verrrrry Niiice! What an excellent mtx mixdown. Very clean, crisp and well balanced...like a good salad. Thanks for the effort. Peace.

Another great Matrix from Hunter! Let's face it, nothing feels quite as right as a beautifully put together Matrix. Hunter seems to have the Midas touch when putting these equally amazing sources and splicing them into one. This show just breathes with new life. Nice work my friend.

Sweeeet Sound This is the sweetest recording
I have heard on this whole site..
way to go...
and the Band is rockin hard!
guitar lot of nice guitar work here by jerry, the franklin was great, very smooth and loose first set, might as well good opener, set the mood...great 2nd set

Slow The matrix here is outstanding.  Hunter has done it again.  The audio quality is superb, and it really sounds like you are in the room.

The show, however, leaves something to be desired.  The songs are simply too slow and lethargic.  With the exception of The Promised Land, the first set seems to go on forever, with one slow song after another.

Help > Slip > Tower starts the second set off right, but the boost of energy simply doesn't last long.  You can actually hear a member of the audience complain about the slow tempo with the opening notes of Friend of the Devil.  The drum solo in the middle of Let It Grow is nice, but it doesn't really lead to much, unfortunately.

The tone is nice, and the band is in tune.  There just isn't much energy here.
